<H1><CENTER>Demonstration 2</CENTER></H1>
<HR>

This demonstration classifies points based on exclusive-or (XOR) logical
operator.  This network has two input nodes, 3 middle nodes and one
output node.  Sources are found in com.digiburo.backprop1b.demo2

<P>
The input nodes contain the logical inputs (substitute 0 as false
and 1 as true).  The training set consists of this simple truth table:
<TABLE BORDER>
  <TR><TH>X   <TH>Y   <TH>Output
  <TR><TD>0.0 <TD>0.0 <TD>0.0
  <TR><TD>0.0 <TD>1.0 <TD>1.0
  <TR><TD>1.0 <TD>0.0 <TD>1.0
  <TR><TD>1.0 <TD>1.0 <TD>0.0
</TABLE>

<P>
To recreate the demo:

<OL>
<LI>Obtain backprop1.jar (download or build).  
    Update $CLASSPATH to include jar file.
    Package name is com.digiburo.demo2 so ensure you type the
    correct command (i.e. java com.digiburo.backprop1b.demo2.Trainer
    to train network).
<LI>The Trainer utility performs training as described above and
    produces a file named 'demo2.serial' after the network has been trained.
    'demo2.serial' contains a serialized Network class.
<LI>The Tester utility accepts a Network class file 'demo2.serial' and
    tests points between [0, 1] at 0.1 intervals.  Here is a graph of
    the output: <A HREF="./demo2_test.png"> Sample Demo2 Test Set</A>
</OL>

The <A HREF="./demo2_test.png"> Sample Demo2 Test Set</A>
graph illustrates response from the trained network.  
Compare the graph to the table above, note the response for (0, 1)
and (1, 0) is in the dotted area while (0, 0) and (1, 1) is
in the clear area.  The network correctly recognizes patterns as trained.

